# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bwf-world-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-men-s-doubles] The **1977 IBF World Championships** took place 1977 in Malmö, Sweden.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-men-s-doubles] Following the results of the men's doubles.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-men-s-singles] The **1977 BWF World Championships** took place from May 3–8, 1977 in Malmö, Sweden.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-men-s-singles] This was the inaugural edition of the World Championships with the joint top seeds being Liem Swie King and Flemming Delfs.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-mixed-doubles] The **First IBF World Championships** took place 1977 in Malmö, Sweden.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-mixed-doubles] Following the results of the women's doubles.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-women-s-doubles] IBF World Championships** took place 1977 in Malmö, Sweden.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships-women-s-singles] Following the results of the women's singles.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships] The **1977 IBF World Championships** was the inaugural badminton championships sanctioned by the International Badminton Federation.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships] It was held in Malmö Isstadion, Malmö, Sweden from 3 to 8 May 1977.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1977-ibf-world-championships] M. the King of Sweden was present throughout the whole of the final day of the tournament.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1978-wbf-world-championships] The **1978 WBF World Championships** took place in November 1978 in Bangkok, Thailand.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1978-wbf-world-championships] This event was followed by Invitational Championships which took place in the month of February earlier this year in Hong Kong.
[src:bwf-world-championships/1978-wbf-world-championships] It was the first of the two editions of the world championships organised by the WBF, which was a rival organisation of the Badminton World Federation.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] The **BWF World Championships** is a badminton tournament organized by the Badminton World Federation.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] It's the most prestigious badminton competition, offering the most ranking points, along with the Summer Olympics badminton events introduced in 1992.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] The winners of the tournament are World Champions of the sport and are awarded a gold medal.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] The tournament started in 1977 and was held once every three years until 1983.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] However, the International Badminton Federation faced difficulty in hosting the first two events as the World Badminton Federation, which later merged with the IBF to form one badminton federation, hosted the same tournament a year after the IBF World Championships with the same goals.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Since 1985, the tournament became biennial and played once every two years until 2005.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Starting 2006, the tournament was changed to an annual event on the BWF calendar.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] The tournament is not held during the Summer Olympics years to avoid schedule conflicts.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] As of 2025, only 22 countries have achieved at least a bronze medal in the tournament: 11 from Asia, eight from Europe, two from North America and one from Oceania.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Africa is the only confederation that has not won a medal.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Canada is the newest country to won a medal in 2025.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] At the age of 18, Ratchanok Inthanon became the youngest winner of a singles title at the Championships.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Ratchanok was less than 3 months older than Jang Hye-ock was when she won the women's doubles title at the 1995 Championships.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] From 1977 up to 2001, the medals were usually divided among five countries, namely China, Korea, Denmark, Indonesia, Malaysia.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] However, in 2003, the winners included seven countries and in 2005 and 2025 the medal board contained a record high of ten countries.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Tony Gunawan also bears the distinction of winning a gold medal in Men's Doubles, representing two countries, 2001 partnering with Halim Haryanto for Indonesia and in 2005 partnering with Howard Bach to give the United States its first medal in the competition.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] The 2005 edition also brought new faces to the mixed doubles event which had been dominated by China and Korea since 1997.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] With the retirement of defending champions and two-time winners Kim Dong-moon/Ra Kyung-min (Korea), Nova Widianto/Liliyana Natsir won Indonesia's first mixed doubles gold since 1980 when Christian Hadinata/Imelda Wiguna won it last for Indonesia.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Below is the list of the most successful players ever, with 3 or more gold medals.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Below is the gold medalists shown based by category and countries after the 2023 BWF World Championships.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] China has been the most successful in the World Championships ever since its inception in 1977.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] They were the only country ever to achieve a shutout of the medals which they did in 1987, 2010 and 2011.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Korea won on the superior of two silver medals to China's one and thus Korea became the overall winner.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] China won on superior of four silver medals to Indonesia's one and thus China became the overall winner.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] China won on the superior of two silver medals to Indonesia's none and thus China became the overall winner.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] China won on superior of four bronze medals to Japan's two and thus China became the overall winner.
[src:bwf-world-championships/bwf-world-championships] Due to the disqualification on suspicion of violation of anti-doping regulations, the 2014 silver medalist Lee Chong Wei was stripped of his medal and thus the medal count does not add up.
